  "title": "InstantSearchNext default routing drops search query param from URL upon hydration",
  "body": "### 🐛 Current behavior\n\nWhen using `<InstantSearchNext routing={true}>` Algolia will correctly display search hits for a query when it is passed as an url param like `mypage.com/search?query=stuff` (assuming that an app router page named `search` exists, that mounts InstantSearchNext). But the `query` param gets dropped from the URL upon hydration.\n\nWe're currently using the following workaround to always add the query to the URL, if it exists:\n\n```tsx\n    <InstantSearchNext \n        routing={{\n            router: {\n                createURL({ qsModule, location, routeState }) {\n                    const { origin, pathname, hash } = location;\n                    const queryString = qsModule.stringify({\n                        ...(query && { query }),\n                        ...routeState,\n                    });\n\n                    return `${origin}${pathname}?${queryString}${hash}`;\n                },\n            },\n        }}\n    >\n```\n\n### 🔍 Steps to reproduce\n\nThe `query` url param gets deleted upon hydration when using the default router. Setting/changing the filters/sorting settings will work and will correctly be persisted in the URL - only the search query param doesn't.\n\n### Live reproduction\n\nno sandbox for InstantSearchNext available\n\n### 💭 Expected behavior\n\nThe `query` param should persist in the URL when using the default router.\n\n### Package version\n\nreact-instantsearch: 7.16.1, react-instantsearch-nextjs: 1.0.0\n\n### Operating system\n\n_No response_\n\n### Browser\n\n_No response_\n\n### Code of Conduct\n\n- [x] I agree to follow this project's Code of Conduct",
